The paper also deals with ranking and unranking operations, which are typically studied in the context of combinatorics and discrete mathematics, suggesting a possible fit with the sub-category cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science). The use of pairing and tupling functions, as well as the Ackermann encoding, suggests a possible fit with the sub-category cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory), which deals with the study of formal languages and their properties. The use of factoradics and Lehmer codes for ranking and unranking permutations suggests a possible fit with the sub-category cs.CC (Computational Complexity), which deals with the study of the computational complexity of algorithms and problems. Finally, the use of Haskell as a programming language suggests a possible fit with the sub-category cs.PL (Programming Languages), which deals with the study of programming languages and their properties.
